Evaluation of Web Service Compositions
Alumnus: Thiago Rodrigues Colucci
MAC499 - Bachelors Graduation Project

With the development of the Internet, the complexity and scale of applications increased highly. Massive Web applications such as Gmail, Google Docs and Amazon are now developed by decoupling their tasks using Web Services. In addition, companies such as Amazon provide
services, exporting them via W3C-compatible Web Service interfaces. Developers can use these available services as building blocks to compose more sophisticated applications.
In this context, Orchestration and Choreography of Web services emerged; they are techniques that use descriptive languages and pre-existing services to create new composite services.

text.tspan: Why to create Web Service Composition?

flowRoot.flowPara: Web Services are a means to enable the interoperability among application components over the Internet. They are defined as a set of W3C standards, using HTTP for the transport layer and XML serialization for data interchange.

Web Services are a fundamental component of a programming model called Service Oriented Architecture (SOA). In this model, services are self-describing and self-contained, leading to the development of
distributed systems based on loosely-coupled distributed modules.
Orchestration of Web Services is a method of service composition in which a central node controls the logic of the entire process.

This node has the responsibility to manage the process, choosing which services will be invoked, how messages are exchanged between these services and how to proceed with the possible exceptions and failures.The most popular language used for orquestrations is BPEL (Business Processes Execution Language), described only with XML markers. It has structures to invoke services, handling exceptions and controlling flows (such as while's and if's).

For the execution of the experiments, we created a generator of synthetic compositions. This generator is parametrized with the number of children in each node and the depth of the tree, which may represent either an orchestration, when analyzing only a node and its children, or as a Choreography, when we look at the tree as a whole.
Using a Ruby script, we instantiate each node in a different Amazon EC2 (Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud) virtual machine.

Web Service Choreography is a form of service composition in which there is no single node that controls the entire process, i.e., control is distributed throughout the system. In a choreography, the interaction protocol among several partner services is defined from a

partner services is defined from a global perspective. At run-time, each participant in a choreography performs a role and interacts with its neighboring participants. As there is no single point of control, and therefore, no single point of failure, there is a better potential for building scalable systems than in the case of centralized orchestrations.

Although there have been a few attempts by the W3C and OMG to specify standard languages to define choreographies, up to the moment there are no implementations that allow the enactment of choreographies specified in standard languages.
